<subSubSection id="EDB3BFE78774FFF5FF33FD6582CBBB7A" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="A516EC6C8774FFF5FF33FD6582CBBB7A" blockId="36.[140,1108,694,1672]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">
<emphasis id="97DD307E8774FFF5FF33FD658019BAF7" bold="true" box="[140,259,694,720]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" reason="1">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. Th is species can be confused only with 
<taxonomicName id="62A997EF8774FFF5FD7BFD64827ABAF6" authorityName="Lingafelter &amp; Micheli" authorityYear="2009" baseAuthorityName="Fisher" baseAuthorityYear="1942" box="[708,864,695,721]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Leptostylopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="viridicomus">
<emphasis id="97DD307E8774FFF5FD7BFD64827ABAF6" box="[708,864,695,721]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">L. viridicomus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but 
<taxonomicName id="62A997EF8774FFF5FC25FD648533BAF6" authorityName="Lingafelter &amp; Micheli" authorityYear="2009" box="[922,1065,695,721]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Leptostylopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="chlorescens">
<emphasis id="97DD307E8774FFF5FC25FD648533BAF6" box="[922,1065,695,721]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">L. chlorescens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has even more pronounced iridescent green pubescence over most of the integument. The dorsal tubercles (in particular the median and anterolaterals) are more highly elevated in 
<taxonomicName id="62A997EF8774FFF5FF14FCF28026BB1D" authorityName="Lingafelter &amp; Micheli" authorityYear="2009" box="[171,316,800,826]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Leptostylopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="chlorescens">
<emphasis id="97DD307E8774FFF5FF14FCF28026BB1D" box="[171,316,800,826]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">L. chlorescens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
than in 
<taxonomicName id="62A997EF8774FFF5FE1FFCF28324BB1D" authorityName="Lingafelter &amp; Micheli" authorityYear="2009" baseAuthorityName="Fisher" baseAuthorityYear="1942" box="[416,574,800,826]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Leptostylopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="viridicomus">
<emphasis id="97DD307E8774FFF5FE1FFCF28324BB1D" box="[416,574,800,826]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">L. viridicomus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Th e apex of the elytron in 
<taxonomicName id="62A997EF8774FFF5FC3EFCF28508BB1D" authorityName="Lingafelter &amp; Micheli" authorityYear="2009" box="[897,1042,800,826]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Leptostylopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="chlorescens">
<emphasis id="97DD307E8774FFF5FC3EFCF28508BB1D" box="[897,1042,800,826]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">L. chlorescens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a distinctive white macula that has anteriorly directed, fingerlike extensions.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
